ls: List directory contents.

Example: ls, ls -l (long format), ls -a (including hidden files).
cd: Change directory.

Example: cd /path/to/directory.
pwd: Print working directory (displays the current directory).

Example: pwd.
mkdir: Make directory.

Example: mkdir directory_name.
rmdir: Remove directory (directory must be empty).

Example: rmdir directory_name.
rm: Remove files or directories.

Example: rm file.txt, rm -r directory_name (recursive removal).
cp: Copy files and directories.

Example: cp file.txt destination_directory.
mv: Move (rename) files and directories.

Example: mv file.txt new_name.txt, mv file.txt /path/to/new/location.
cat: Concatenate and display files.

Example: cat file.txt.
less: Display file contents one screen at a time.

Example: less file.txt.
head: Display the beginning of a file.

Example: head file.txt.
tail: Display the end of a file.

Example: tail file.txt.
grep: Search for patterns in files.

Example: grep "pattern" file.txt.
chmod: Change file permissions.

Example: chmod +x script.sh (adds execute permission).
chown: Change file owner and group.

Example: chown user:group file.txt.
passwd: Change user password.

Example: passwd.
man: Display the manual pages for commands.

Example: man ls (displays the manual for the ls command).
df: Display disk space usage.

Example: df -h (human-readable format).
du: Display disk usage of files and directories.

Example: du -sh directory_name (summarized and human-readable).
wget: Download files from the internet.

Example: wget URL.
